[Context: Alternatives, Inspiration and Comparisons > Previous tools > [Django REST Framework](https://www.django-rest-framework.org/)]

### Django REST Framework
Django REST framework was created to be a flexible toolkit for building Web APIs using Django underneath, to improve its API capabilities.
It is used by many companies including Mozilla, Red Hat and Eventbrite.
It was one of the first examples of [BOLD:automatic API documentation], and this was specifically one of the first ideas that inspired "the search for" [BOLD:FastAPI].
/// note
Django REST Framework was created by Tom Christie. The same creator of Starlette and Uvicorn, on which [BOLD:FastAPI] is based.
///
/// check | Inspired [BOLD:FastAPI] to
Have an automatic API documentation web user interface.
///

[Context: Alternatives, Inspiration and Comparisons > Previous tools > [Webargs](https://webargs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/)]

### Webargs
Another big feature required by APIs is parsing data from incoming requests.
Webargs is a tool that was made to provide that on top of several frameworks, including Flask.
It uses Marshmallow underneath to do the data validation. And it was created by the same developers.
It's a great tool and I have used it a lot too, before having [BOLD:FastAPI].
/// info
Webargs was created by the same Marshmallow developers.
///
/// check | Inspired [BOLD:FastAPI] to
Have automatic validation of incoming request data.
///

[Context: Alternatives, Inspiration and Comparisons > Previous tools > [Sanic](https://sanic.readthedocs.io/en/latest/)]

### Sanic
It was one of the first extremely fast Python frameworks based on [CODE: asyncio]. It was made to be very similar to Flask.
/// note | Technical Details
It used [[CODE: uvloop]](https://github.com/MagicStack/uvloop) instead of the default Python [CODE: asyncio] loop. That's what made it so fast.
It clearly inspired Uvicorn and Starlette, that are currently faster than Sanic in open benchmarks.
///
/// check | Inspired [BOLD:FastAPI] to
Find a way to have a crazy performance.
That's why [BOLD:FastAPI] is based on Starlette, as it is the fastest framework available (tested by third-party benchmarks).
///

[Context: Alternatives, Inspiration and Comparisons > Used by **FastAPI** > [Starlette](https://www.starlette.dev/)]

### Starlette
Starlette is a lightweight ASGI framework/toolkit, which is ideal for building high-performance asyncio services.
It is very simple and intuitive. It's designed to be easily extensible, and have modular components.
It has:
[ITALIC: Seriously impressive performance.
] WebSocket support.
[ITALIC: In-process background tasks.
] Startup and shutdown events.
[ITALIC: Test client built on HTTPX.
] CORS, GZip, Static Files, Streaming responses.
[ITALIC: Session and Cookie support.
] 100% test coverage.
[ITALIC: 100% type annotated codebase.
] Few hard dependencies.
Starlette is currently the fastest Python framework tested. Only surpassed by Uvicorn, which is not a framework, but a server.
Starlette provides all the basic web microframework functionality.
But it doesn't provide automatic data validation, serialization or documentation.
That's one of the main things that [BOLD:FastAPI] adds on top, all based on Python type hints (using Pydantic). That, plus the dependency injection system, security utilities, OpenAPI schema generation, etc.
/// note | Technical Details
ASGI is a new "standard" being developed by Django core team members. It is still not a "Python standard" (a PEP), although they are in the process of doing that.
Nevertheless, it is already being used as a "standard" by several tools. This greatly improves interoperability, as you could switch Uvicorn for any other ASGI server (like Daphne or Hypercorn), or you could add ASGI compatible tools, like [CODE: python-socketio].
///
/// check | [BOLD:FastAPI] uses it to
Handle all the core web parts. Adding features on top.
The class [CODE: FastAPI] itself inherits directly from the class [CODE: Starlette].
So, anything that you can do with Starlette, you can do it directly with [BOLD:FastAPI], as it is basically Starlette on steroids.
///

