## Create and Use Env Vars
You can [BOLD:create] and use environment variables in the [BOLD:shell (terminal)], without needing Python:
//// tab | Linux, macOS, Windows Bash

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: // You could create an env var MY[ITALIC:NAME with $ expo...]

////
//// tab | Windows PowerShell

[CODE]BLOCK[ITALIC:1: // Create an env var MY]NAME $ $Env:MY_NAME = "Wad...]

////

[Context: Environment Variables > `PATH` Environment Variable]

## [CODE: PATH] Environment Variable
There is a [BOLD:special] environment variable called [BOLD:[CODE: PATH]] that is used by the operating systems (Linux, macOS, Windows) to find programs to run.
The value of the variable [CODE: PATH] is a long string that is made of directories separated by a colon [CODE: :] on Linux and macOS, and by a semicolon [CODE: ;] on Windows.
For example, the [CODE: PATH] environment variable could look like this:
//// tab | Linux, macOS
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: /usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin...]
This means that the system should look for programs in the directories:
[ITALIC: [CODE: /usr/local/bin]
] [CODE: /usr/bin]
[ITALIC: [CODE: /bin]
] [CODE: /usr/sbin]
[ITALIC: [CODE: /sbin]
////
//// tab | Windows
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: C:\Program Files\Python312\Scripts;C:\Program File...]
This means that the system should look for programs in the directories:
] [CODE: C:\Program Files\Python312\Scripts]
[ITALIC: [CODE: C:\Program Files\Python312]
] [CODE: C:\Windows\System32]
////
When you type a [BOLD:command] in the terminal, the operating system [BOLD:looks for] the program in [BOLD:each of those directories] listed in the [CODE: PATH] environment variable.
For example, when you type [CODE: python] in the terminal, the operating system looks for a program called [CODE: python] in the [BOLD:first directory] in that list.
If it finds it, then it will [BOLD:use it]. Otherwise it keeps looking in the [BOLD:other directories].

