[Context: Features > FastAPI features > Based on open standards]

### Based on open standards
[ITALIC: [BOLD:OpenAPI] for API creation, including declarations of path operations, parameters, request bodies, security, etc.
] Automatic data model documentation with [BOLD:JSON Schema] (as OpenAPI itself is based on JSON Schema).
[ITALIC: Designed around these standards, after a meticulous study. Instead of an afterthought layer on top.
] This also allows using automatic [BOLD:client code generation] in many languages.

[Context: Features > FastAPI features > Validation]

### Validation
[ITALIC: Validation for most (or all?) Python [BOLD:data types], including:
] JSON objects ([CODE: dict]).
[ITALIC: JSON array ([CODE: list]) defining item types.
] String ([CODE: str]) fields, defining min and max lengths.
[ITALIC: Numbers ([CODE: int], [CODE: float]) with min and max values, etc.
] Validation for more exotic types, like:
[ITALIC: URL.
] Email.
[ITALIC: UUID.
] ...and others.
All the validation is handled by the well-established and robust [BOLD:Pydantic].

[Context: Features > FastAPI features > Dependency Injection]

### Dependency Injection
FastAPI includes an extremely easy to use, but extremely powerful Dependency Injection system.
[ITALIC: Even dependencies can have dependencies, creating a hierarchy or [BOLD:"graph" of dependencies].
] All [BOLD:automatically handled] by the framework.
[ITALIC: All the dependencies can require data from requests and [BOLD:augment the path operation] constraints and automatic documentation.
] [BOLD:Automatic validation] even for [ITALIC:path operation] parameters defined in dependencies.
[ITALIC: Support for complex user authentication systems, [BOLD:database connections], etc.
] [BOLD:No compromise] with databases, frontends, etc. But easy integration with all of them.

[Context: Features > Pydantic features]

## Pydantic features
[BOLD:FastAPI] is fully compatible with (and based on) [BOLD:Pydantic]. So, any additional Pydantic code you have, will also work.
Including external libraries also based on Pydantic, as ORMs, ODMs for databases.
This also means that in many cases you can pass the same object you get from a request [BOLD:directly to the database], as everything is validated automatically.
The same applies the other way around, in many cases you can just pass the object you get from the database [BOLD:directly to the client].
With [BOLD:FastAPI] you get all of [BOLD:Pydantic]'s features (as FastAPI is based on Pydantic for all the data handling):
[ITALIC: [BOLD:No brainfuck]:
] No new schema definition micro-language to learn.
[ITALIC: If you know Python types you know how to use Pydantic.
] Plays nicely with your [BOLD:IDE/linter/brain]:
[ITALIC: Because pydantic data structures are just instances of classes you define; auto-completion, linting, mypy and your intuition should all work properly with your validated data.
] Validate [BOLD:complex structures]:
[ITALIC: Use of hierarchical Pydantic models, Python [CODE: typing]’s [CODE: List] and [CODE: Dict], etc.
] And validators allow complex data schemas to be clearly and easily defined, checked and documented as JSON Schema.
[ITALIC: You can have deeply [BOLD:nested JSON] objects and have them all validated and annotated.
] [BOLD:Extensible]:
[ITALIC: Pydantic allows custom data types to be defined or you can extend validation with methods on a model decorated with the validator decorator.
] 100% test coverage.

