## Edit PR Titles
[ITALIC: Edit the PR title to start with an emoji from gitmoji.
] Use the emoji character, not the GitHub code. So, use [CODE: ] instead of [CODE: :bug:]. This is so that it shows up correctly outside of GitHub, for example in the release notes.
[ITALIC: For translations use the [CODE: ] emoji ("globe with meridians").
] Start the title with a verb. For example [CODE: Add], [CODE: Refactor], [CODE: Fix], etc. This way the title will say the action that the PR does. Like [CODE: Add support for teleporting], instead of [CODE: Teleporting wasn't working, so this PR fixes it].
[ITALIC: Edit the text of the PR title to start in "imperative", like giving an order. So, instead of [CODE: Adding support for teleporting] use [CODE: Add support for teleporting].
] Try to make the title descriptive about what it achieves. If it's a feature, try to describe it, for example [CODE: Add support for teleporting] instead of [CODE: Create TeleportAdapter class].
[ITALIC: Do not finish the title with a period ([CODE: .]).
] When the PR is for a translation, start with the [CODE: ] and then [CODE: Add {language} translation for] and then the translated file path. For example:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: Add Spanish translation for `docs/es/docs/telepo...]
Once the PR is merged, a GitHub Action (latest-changes) will use the PR title to update the latest changes automatically.
So, having a nice PR title will not only look nice in GitHub, but also in the release notes.

