[Context: Repository Management Tasks > Add Labels to PRs]

## Add Labels to PRs
The same GitHub Action latest-changes uses one label in the PR to decide the section in the release notes to put this PR in.
Make sure you use a supported label from the latest-changes list of labels:
[ITALIC: [CODE: breaking]: Breaking Changes
] Existing code will break if they update the version without changing their code. This rarely happens, so this label is not frequently used.
[ITALIC: [CODE: security]: Security Fixes
] This is for security fixes, like vulnerabilities. It would almost never be used.
[ITALIC: [CODE: feature]: Features
] New features, adding support for things that didn't exist before.
[ITALIC: [CODE: bug]: Fixes
] Something that was supported didn't work, and this fixes it. There are many PRs that claim to be bug fixes because the user is doing something in an unexpected way that is not supported, but they considered it what should be supported by default. Many of these are actually features or refactors. But in some cases there's an actual bug.
[ITALIC: [CODE: refactor]: Refactors
] This is normally for changes to the internal code that don't change the behavior. Normally it improves maintainability, or enables future features, etc.
[ITALIC: [CODE: upgrade]: Upgrades
] This is for upgrades to direct dependencies from the project, or extra optional dependencies, normally in [CODE: pyproject.toml]. So, things that would affect final users, they would end up receiving the upgrade in their code base once they update. But this is not for upgrades to internal dependencies used for development, testing, docs, etc. Those internal dependencies or GitHub Action versions should be marked as [CODE: internal], not [CODE: upgrade].
[ITALIC: [CODE: docs]: Docs
] Changes in docs. This includes updating the docs, fixing typos. But it doesn't include changes to translations.
[ITALIC: You can normally quickly detect it by going to the "Files changed" tab in the PR and checking if the updated file(s) starts with [CODE: docs/en/docs]. The original version of the docs is always in English, so in [CODE: docs/en/docs].
] [CODE: lang-all]: Translations
[ITALIC: Use this for translations. You can normally quickly detect it by going to the "Files changed" tab in the PR and checking if the updated file(s) starts with [CODE: docs/{some lang}/docs] but not [CODE: docs/en/docs]. For example, [CODE: docs/es/docs].
] [CODE: internal]: Internal
- Use this for changes that only affect how the repo is managed. For example upgrades to internal dependencies, changes in GitHub Actions or scripts, etc.
/// tip
Some tools like Dependabot, will add some labels, like [CODE: dependencies], but have in mind that this label is not used by the [CODE: latest-changes] GitHub Action, so it won't be used in the release notes. Please make sure one of the labels above is added.
///

