## 0.30.0 (2019-06-20)
[ITALIC: Add support for Pydantic's ORM mode:
] Updated documentation about SQL with SQLAlchemy, using Pydantic models with ORM mode, SQLAlchemy models with relations, separation of files, simplification of code and other changes. New docs: SQL (Relational) Databases.
[ITALIC: The new support for ORM mode fixes issues/adds features related to ORMs with lazy-loading, hybrid properties, dynamic/getters (using [CODE: @property] decorators) and several other use cases.
] This applies to ORMs like SQLAlchemy, Peewee, Tortoise ORM, GINO ORM and virtually any other.
[ITALIC: If your ]path operations[ITALIC: return an arbitrary object with attributes (e.g. [CODE: my[ITALIC:item.name] instead of [CODE: my]item["name"]]) AND you use a [CODE: response[ITALIC:model], make sure to update the Pydantic models with [CODE: orm]mode = True] as described in the docs (link above).
] New documentation about receiving plain [CODE: dict]s as request bodies: [Bodies of arbitrary [CODE: dict]s](https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#bodies-of-arbitrary-dicts).
[ITALIC: New documentation about returning arbitrary [CODE: dict]s in responses: [Response with arbitrary [CODE: dict]](https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/extra-models/#response-with-arbitrary-dict).
] [BOLD:Technical Details]:
[ITALIC: When declaring a [CODE: response[ITALIC:model] it is used directly to generate the response content, from whatever was returned from the ]path operation function[ITALIC:.
] Before this, the return content was first passed through [CODE: jsonable]encoder] to ensure it was a "jsonable" object, like a [CODE: dict], instead of an arbitrary object with attributes (like an ORM model). That's why you should make sure to update your Pydantic models for objects with attributes to use [CODE: orm[ITALIC:mode = True].
[ITALIC: If you don't have a [CODE: response]model], the return object will still be passed through [CODE: jsonable[ITALIC:encoder] first.
] When a [CODE: response]model] is declared, the same [CODE: response[ITALIC:model] type declaration won't be used as is, it will be "cloned" to create an new one (a cloned Pydantic [CODE: Field] with all the submodels cloned as well).
[ITALIC: This avoids/fixes a potential security issue: as the returned object is passed directly to Pydantic, if the returned object was a subclass of the [CODE: response]model] (e.g. you return a [CODE: UserInDB] that inherits from [CODE: User] but contains extra fields, like [CODE: hashed[ITALIC:password], and [CODE: User] is used in the [CODE: response]model]), it would still pass the validation (because [CODE: UserInDB] is a subclass of [CODE: User]) and the object would be returned as-is, including the [CODE: hashed[ITALIC:password]. To fix this, the declared [CODE: response]model] is cloned, if it is a Pydantic model class (or contains Pydantic model classes in it, e.g. in a [CODE: List[Item]]), the Pydantic model class(es) will be a different one (the "cloned" one). So, an object that is a subclass won't simply pass the validation and returned as-is, because it is no longer a sub-class of the cloned [CODE: response[ITALIC:model]. Instead, a new Pydantic model object will be created with the contents of the returned object. So, it will be a new object (made with the data from the returned one), and will be filtered by the cloned [CODE: response]model], containing only the declared fields as normally.
] PR #322.
[ITALIC: Remove/clean unused RegEx code in routing. PR #314 by @dmontagu.
] Use default response status code descriptions for additional responses. PR #313 by @duxiaoyao.
- Upgrade Pydantic support to [CODE: 0.28]. PR #320 by @jekirl.

