# Virtual Environments
When you work in Python projects you probably should use a [BOLD:virtual environment] (or a similar mechanism) to isolate the packages you install for each project.
/// info
If you already know about virtual environments, how to create them and use them, you might want to skip this section. 🤓
///
/// tip
A [BOLD:virtual environment] is different than an [BOLD:environment variable].
An [BOLD:environment variable] is a variable in the system that can be used by programs.
A [BOLD:virtual environment] is a directory with some files in it.
///
/// info
This page will teach you how to use [BOLD:virtual environments] and how they work.
If you are ready to adopt a [BOLD:tool that manages everything] for you (including installing Python), try uv.
///

[Context: Virtual Environments > Create a Virtual Environment]

## Create a Virtual Environment
When you start working on a Python project [BOLD:for the first time], create a virtual environment [BOLD:inside your project].
/// tip
You only need to do this [BOLD:once per project], not every time you work.
///
//// tab | [CODE: venv]
To create a virtual environment, you can use the [CODE: venv] module that comes with Python.

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ python -m venv .venv...]

/// details | What that command means
[ITALIC: [CODE: python]: use the program called [CODE: python]
] [CODE: -m]: call a module as a script, we'll tell it which module next
[ITALIC: [CODE: venv]: use the module called [CODE: venv] that normally comes installed with Python
] [CODE: .venv]: create the virtual environment in the new directory [CODE: .venv]
///
////
//// tab | [CODE: uv]
If you have [[CODE: uv]](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv) installed, you can use it to create a virtual environment.

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ uv venv...]

/// tip
By default, [CODE: uv] will create a virtual environment in a directory called [CODE: .venv].
But you could customize it passing an additional argument with the directory name.
///
////
That command creates a new virtual environment in a directory called [CODE: .venv].
/// details | [CODE: .venv] or other name
You could create the virtual environment in a different directory, but there's a convention of calling it [CODE: .venv].
///

[Context: Virtual Environments > Create a Virtual Environment]

