[Context: Virtual Environments > Activate the Virtual Environment]

## Activate the Virtual Environment
Activate the new virtual environment so that any Python command you run or package you install uses it.
/// tip
Do this [BOLD:every time] you start a [BOLD:new terminal session] to work on the project.
///
//// tab | Linux, macOS

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ source .venv/bin/activate...]

////
//// tab | Windows PowerShell

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ .venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1...]

////
//// tab | Windows Bash
Or if you use Bash for Windows (e.g. Git Bash):

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]2: $ source .venv/Scripts/activate...]

////
/// tip
Every time you install a [BOLD:new package] in that environment, [BOLD:activate] the environment again.
This makes sure that if you use a [BOLD:terminal (CLI) program] installed by that package, you use the one from your virtual environment and not any other that could be installed globally, probably with a different version than what you need.
///

[Context: Virtual Environments > Check the Virtual Environment is Active]

## Check the Virtual Environment is Active
Check that the virtual environment is active (the previous command worked).
/// tip
This is [BOLD:optional], but it's a good way to [BOLD:check] that everything is working as expected and you are using the virtual environment you intended.
///
//// tab | Linux, macOS, Windows Bash

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ which python /home/user/code/awesome-project/.ve...]

If it shows the [CODE: python] binary at [CODE: .venv/bin/python], inside of your project (in this case [CODE: awesome-project]), then it worked.
////
//// tab | Windows PowerShell

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ Get-Command python C:\Users\user\code\awesome-pr...]

If it shows the [CODE: python] binary at [CODE: .venv\Scripts\python], inside of your project (in this case [CODE: awesome-project]), then it worked.
////

[Context: Virtual Environments > Upgrade `pip`]

## Upgrade [CODE: pip]
/// tip
If you use [[CODE: uv]](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv) you would use it to install things instead of [CODE: pip], so you don't need to upgrade [CODE: pip].
///
If you are using [CODE: pip] to install packages (it comes by default with Python), you should [BOLD:upgrade] it to the latest version.
Many exotic errors while installing a package are solved by just upgrading [CODE: pip] first.
/// tip
You would normally do this [BOLD:once], right after you create the virtual environment.
///
Make sure the virtual environment is active (with the command above) and then run:

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ python -m pip install --upgrade pip ---> 100%...]

/// tip
Sometimes, you might get a [BOLD:[CODE: No module named pip]] error when trying to upgrade pip.
If this happens, install and upgrade pip using the command below:

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ python -m ensurepip --upgrade ---> 100%...]

This command will install pip if it is not already installed and also ensures that the installed version of pip is at least as recent as the one available in [CODE: ensurepip].
///

[Context: Virtual Environments > Upgrade `pip`]

