[Context: Virtual Environments > Install Packages > Install Packages Directly]

### Install Packages Directly
If you're in a hurry and don't want to use a file to declare your project's package requirements, you can install them directly.
/// tip
It's a (very) good idea to put the packages and versions your program needs in a file (for example [CODE: requirements.txt] or [CODE: pyproject.toml]).
///
//// tab | [CODE: pip]

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ pip install "fastapi[standard]" ---> 100%...]

////
//// tab | [CODE: uv]
If you have [[CODE: uv]](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv):

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ uv pip install "fastapi[standard]" ---> 100%...]

////

[Context: Virtual Environments > Install Packages > Install from `requirements.txt`]

### Install from [CODE: requirements.txt]
If you have a [CODE: requirements.txt], you can now use it to install its packages.
//// tab | [CODE: pip]

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ pip install -r requirements.txt ---> 100%...]

////
//// tab | [CODE: uv]
If you have [[CODE: uv]](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv):

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ uv pip install -r requirements.txt ---> 100%...]

////
/// details | [CODE: requirements.txt]
A [CODE: requirements.txt] with some packages could look like:
```requirements.txt
fastapi[standard]==0.113.0
pydantic==2.8.0
```
///

