[Context: Virtual Environments > What Does Activating a Virtual Environment Mean]

## What Does Activating a Virtual Environment Mean
When you activate a virtual environment, for example with:
//// tab | Linux, macOS

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ source .venv/bin/activate...]

////
//// tab | Windows PowerShell

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: $ .venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1...]

////
//// tab | Windows Bash
Or if you use Bash for Windows (e.g. Git Bash):

[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]2: $ source .venv/Scripts/activate...]

////
That command will create or modify some environment variables that will be available for the next commands.
One of those variables is the [CODE: PATH] variable.
/// tip
You can learn more about the [CODE: PATH] environment variable in the Environment Variables section.
///
Activating a virtual environment adds its path [CODE: .venv/bin] (on Linux and macOS) or [CODE: .venv\Scripts] (on Windows) to the [CODE: PATH] environment variable.
Let's say that before activating the environment, the [CODE: PATH] variable looked like this:
//// tab | Linux, macOS
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]3: /usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin...]
That means that the system would look for programs in:
[ITALIC: [CODE: /usr/bin]
] [CODE: /bin]
[ITALIC: [CODE: /usr/sbin]
] [CODE: /sbin]
////
//// tab | Windows
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]4: C:\Windows\System32...]
That means that the system would look for programs in:
- [CODE: C:\Windows\System32]
////
After activating the virtual environment, the [CODE: PATH] variable would look something like this:
//// tab | Linux, macOS
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]5: /home/user/code/awesome-project/.venv/bin:/usr/bin...]
That means that the system will now start looking first for programs in:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]6: /home/user/code/awesome-project/.venv/bin...]
before looking in the other directories.
So, when you type [CODE: python] in the terminal, the system will find the Python program in
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]7: /home/user/code/awesome-project/.venv/bin/python...]
and use that one.
////
//// tab | Windows
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]8: C:\Users\user\code\awesome-project\.venv\Scripts;C...]
That means that the system will now start looking first for programs in:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]9: C:\Users\user\code\awesome-project\.venv\Scripts...]
before looking in the other directories.
So, when you type [CODE: python] in the terminal, the system will find the Python program in
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]10: C:\Users\user\code\awesome-project\.venv\Scripts\p...]
and use that one.
////
An important detail is that it will put the virtual environment path at the [BOLD:beginning] of the [CODE: PATH] variable. The system will find it [BOLD:before] finding any other Python available. This way, when you run [CODE: python], it will use the Python [BOLD:from the virtual environment] instead of any other [CODE: python] (for example, a [CODE: python] from a global environment).
Activating a virtual environment also changes a couple of other things, but this is one of the most important things it does.

