## Proxy with a stripped path prefix
You could have a proxy that adds a path prefix to your application.
In these cases you can use [CODE: root[ITALIC:path] to configure your application.
The [CODE: root]path] is a mechanism provided by the ASGI specification (that FastAPI is built on, through Starlette).
The [CODE: root[ITALIC:path] is used to handle these specific cases.
And it's also used internally when mounting sub-applications.
Having a proxy with a stripped path prefix, in this case, means that you could declare a path at [CODE: /app] in your code, but then, you add a layer on top (the proxy) that would put your [BOLD:FastAPI] application under a path like [CODE: /api/v1].
In this case, the original path [CODE: /app] would actually be served at [CODE: /api/v1/app].
Even though all your code is written assuming there's just [CODE: /app].
```python
@app.get("/app")
def read]main(request: Request):
```
And the proxy would be [BOLD:"stripping"] the [BOLD:path prefix] on the fly before transmitting the request to the app server (probably Uvicorn via FastAPI CLI), keeping your application convinced that it is being served at [CODE: /app], so that you don't have to update all your code to include the prefix [CODE: /api/v1].
Up to here, everything would work as normally.
But then, when you open the integrated docs UI (the frontend), it would expect to get the OpenAPI schema at [CODE: /openapi.json], instead of [CODE: /api/v1/openapi.json].
So, the frontend (that runs in the browser) would try to reach [CODE: /openapi.json] and wouldn't be able to get the OpenAPI schema.
Because we have a proxy with a path prefix of [CODE: /api/v1] for our app, the frontend needs to fetch the OpenAPI schema at [CODE: /api/v1/openapi.json].
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: graph LR browser("Browser") proxy["Proxy on http:/...]
/// tip
The IP [CODE: 0.0.0.0] is commonly used to mean that the program listens on all the IPs available in that machine/server.
///
The docs UI would also need the OpenAPI schema to declare that this API [CODE: server] is located at [CODE: /api/v1] (behind the proxy). For example:
```JSON hl_lines="4-8"
{
"openapi": "3.1.0",
// More stuff here
"servers": [
{
"url": "/api/v1"
}
],
"paths": {
// More stuff here
}
}
```
In this example, the "Proxy" could be something like [BOLD:Traefik]. And the server would be something like FastAPI CLI with [BOLD:Uvicorn], running your FastAPI application.

