### Examples of Replication Tools and Strategies
There can be several approaches to achieve this, and I'll tell you more about specific strategies in the next chapters, for example when talking about Docker and containers.
The main constraint to consider is that there has to be a [BOLD:single] component handling the [BOLD:port] in the [BOLD:public IP]. And then it has to have a way to [BOLD:transmit] the communication to the replicated [BOLD:processes/workers].
Here are some possible combinations and strategies:
[ITALIC: [BOLD:Uvicorn] with [CODE: --workers]
] One Uvicorn [BOLD:process manager] would listen on the [BOLD:IP] and [BOLD:port], and it would start [BOLD:multiple Uvicorn worker processes].
[ITALIC: [BOLD:Kubernetes] and other distributed [BOLD:container systems]
] Something in the [BOLD:Kubernetes] layer would listen on the [BOLD:IP] and [BOLD:port]. The replication would be by having [BOLD:multiple containers], each with [BOLD:one Uvicorn process] running.
[ITALIC: [BOLD:Cloud services] that handle this for you
] The cloud service will probably [BOLD:handle replication for you]. It would possibly let you define [BOLD:a process to run], or a [BOLD:container image] to use, in any case, it would most probably be [BOLD:a single Uvicorn process], and the cloud service would be in charge of replicating it.
/// tip
Don't worry if some of these items about [BOLD:containers], Docker, or Kubernetes don't make a lot of sense yet.
I'll tell you more about container images, Docker, Kubernetes, etc. in a future chapter: FastAPI in Containers - Docker.
///

