[Context: About FastAPI versions > About versions]

## About versions
Following the Semantic Versioning conventions, any version below [CODE: 1.0.0] could potentially add breaking changes.
FastAPI also follows the convention that any "PATCH" version change is for bug fixes and non-breaking changes.
/// tip
The "PATCH" is the last number, for example, in [CODE: 0.2.3], the PATCH version is [CODE: 3].
///
So, you should be able to pin to a version like:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: fastapi>=0.45.0,<0.46.0...]
Breaking changes and new features are added in "MINOR" versions.
/// tip
The "MINOR" is the number in the middle, for example, in [CODE: 0.2.3], the MINOR version is [CODE: 2].
///

[Context: Use Old 403 Authentication Error Status Codes]

# Use Old 403 Authentication Error Status Codes
Before FastAPI version [CODE: 0.122.0], when the integrated security utilities returned an error to the client after a failed authentication, they used the HTTP status code [CODE: 403 Forbidden].
Starting with FastAPI version [CODE: 0.122.0], they use the more appropriate HTTP status code [CODE: 401 Unauthorized], and return a sensible [CODE: WWW-Authenticate] header in the response, following the HTTP specifications, RFC 7235, RFC 9110.
But if for some reason your clients depend on the old behavior, you can revert to it by overriding the method [CODE: make[ITALIC:not]authenticated[ITALIC:error] in your security classes.
For example, you can create a subclass of [CODE: HTTPBearer] that returns a [CODE: 403 Forbidden] error instead of the default [CODE: 401 Unauthorized] error:
```python
class HTTPBearer403(HTTPBearer):
def make]not[ITALIC:authenticated]error(self) -> HTTPException:
return HTTPException(
status[ITALIC:code=status.HTTP]403_FORBIDDEN, detail="Not authenticated"
)
```
/// tip
Notice that the function returns the exception instance, it doesn't raise it. The raising is done in the rest of the internal code.
///

