## An example file structure
Let's say you have a file structure like this:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: . app [BOLD:init].py main.py de...]
/// tip
There are several [CODE: [BOLD:init].py] files: one in each directory or subdirectory.
This is what allows importing code from one file into another.
For example, in [CODE: app/main.py] you could have a line like:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]1: from app.routers import items...]
///
[ITALIC: The [CODE: app] directory contains everything. And it has an empty file [CODE: app/[BOLD:init].py], so it is a "Python package" (a collection of "Python modules"): [CODE: app].
] It contains an [CODE: app/main.py] file. As it is inside a Python package (a directory with a file [CODE: [BOLD:init].py]), it is a "module" of that package: [CODE: app.main].
[ITALIC: There's also an [CODE: app/dependencies.py] file, just like [CODE: app/main.py], it is a "module": [CODE: app.dependencies].
] There's a subdirectory [CODE: app/routers/] with another file [CODE: [BOLD:init].py], so it's a "Python subpackage": [CODE: app.routers].
[ITALIC: The file [CODE: app/routers/items.py] is inside a package, [CODE: app/routers/], so, it's a submodule: [CODE: app.routers.items].
] The same with [CODE: app/routers/users.py], it's another submodule: [CODE: app.routers.users].
[ITALIC: There's also a subdirectory [CODE: app/internal/] with another file [CODE: [BOLD:init].py], so it's another "Python subpackage": [CODE: app.internal].
] And the file [CODE: app/internal/admin.py] is another submodule: [CODE: app.internal.admin].

The same file structure with comments:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]2: . app # "app" is a Python package __init...]

