## Another module with [CODE: APIRouter]
Let's say you also have the endpoints dedicated to handling "items" from your application in the module at [CODE: app/routers/items.py].
You have [ITALIC:path operations] for:
[ITALIC: [CODE: /items/]
] [CODE: /items/{item[ITALIC:id}]
It's all the same structure as with [CODE: app/routers/users.py].
But we want to be smarter and simplify the code a bit.
We know all the [ITALIC:path operations] in this module have the same:
[ITALIC: Path [CODE: prefix]: [CODE: /items].
] [CODE: tags]: (just one tag: [CODE: items]).
[ITALIC: Extra [CODE: responses].
] [CODE: dependencies]: they all need that [CODE: X-Token] dependency we created.
So, instead of adding all that to each [ITALIC:path operation], we can add it to the [CODE: APIRouter].
{[ITALIC: ../../docs]src/bigger[ITALIC:applications/app]an[ITALIC:py310/routers/items.py hl[5:10,16,21] title["app/routers/items.py"] ]}
As the path of each [ITALIC:path operation] has to start with [CODE: /], like in:
```Python hl]lines="1"
@router.get("/{item[ITALIC:id}")
async def read]item(item[ITALIC:id: str):
...
```
...the prefix must not include a final [CODE: /].
So, the prefix in this case is [CODE: /items].
We can also add a list of [CODE: tags] and extra [CODE: responses] that will be applied to all the [ITALIC:path operations] included in this router.
And we can add a list of [CODE: dependencies] that will be added to all the [ITALIC:path operations] in the router and will be executed/solved for each request made to them.
/// tip
Note that, much like dependencies in [ITALIC:path operation decorators], no value will be passed to your [ITALIC:path operation function].
///
The end result is that the item paths are now:
[ITALIC: [CODE: /items/]
] [CODE: /items/{item]id}]
...as we intended.
[ITALIC: They will be marked with a list of tags that contain a single string [CODE: "items"].
] These "tags" are especially useful for the automatic interactive documentation systems (using OpenAPI).
[ITALIC: All of them will include the predefined [CODE: responses].
] All these [ITALIC:path operations] will have the list of [CODE: dependencies] evaluated/executed before them.
[ITALIC: If you also declare dependencies in a specific ]path operation[ITALIC:, [BOLD:they will be executed too].
] The router dependencies are executed first, then the [[CODE: dependencies] in the decorator](dependencies/dependencies-in-path-operation-decorators.md), and then the normal parameter dependencies.
[ITALIC: You can also add [[CODE: Security] dependencies with [CODE: scopes]](../advanced/security/oauth2-scopes.md).
/// tip
Having [CODE: dependencies] in the [CODE: APIRouter] can be used, for example, to require authentication for a whole group of ]path operations*. Even if the dependencies are not added individually to each one of them.
///
/// check
The [CODE: prefix], [CODE: tags], [CODE: responses], and [CODE: dependencies] parameters are (as in many other cases) just a feature from [BOLD:FastAPI] to help you avoid code duplication.
///

