# Cookie Parameter Models
If you have a group of [BOLD:cookies] that are related, you can create a [BOLD:Pydantic model] to declare them.
This would allow you to [BOLD:re-use the model] in [BOLD:multiple places] and also to declare validations and metadata for all the parameters at once.
/// note
This is supported since FastAPI version [CODE: 0.115.0]. 🤓
///
/// tip
This same technique applies to [CODE: Query], [CODE: Cookie], and [CODE: Header].
///

[Context: Cookie Parameters > Declare `Cookie` parameters]

## Declare [CODE: Cookie] parameters
Then declare the cookie parameters using the same structure as with [CODE: Path] and [CODE: Query].
You can define the default value as well as all the extra validation or annotation parameters:
```python
async def read[ITALIC:items(ads]id: Annotated[str | None, Cookie()] = None):
return {"ads[ITALIC:id": ads]id}
```
/// note | Technical Details
[CODE: Cookie] is a "sister" class of [CODE: Path] and [CODE: Query]. It also inherits from the same common [CODE: Param] class.
But remember that when you import [CODE: Query], [CODE: Path], [CODE: Cookie] and others from [CODE: fastapi], those are actually functions that return special classes.
///
/// info
To declare cookies, you need to use [CODE: Cookie], because otherwise the parameters would be interpreted as query parameters.
///
/// info
Have in mind that, as [BOLD:browsers handle cookies] in special ways and behind the scenes, they [BOLD:don't] easily allow [BOLD:JavaScript] to touch them.
If you go to the [BOLD:API docs UI] at [CODE: /docs] you will be able to see the [BOLD:documentation] for cookies for your [ITALIC:path operations].
But even if you [BOLD:fill the data] and click "Execute", because the docs UI works with [BOLD:JavaScript], the cookies won't be sent, and you will see an [BOLD:error] message as if you didn't write any values.
///

