## Other data types
Here are some of the additional data types you can use:
[ITALIC: [CODE: UUID]:
] A standard "Universally Unique Identifier", common as an ID in many databases and systems.
[ITALIC: In requests and responses will be represented as a [CODE: str].
] [CODE: datetime.datetime]:
[ITALIC: A Python [CODE: datetime.datetime].
] In requests and responses will be represented as a [CODE: str] in ISO 8601 format, like: [CODE: 2008-09-15T15:53:00+05:00].
[ITALIC: [CODE: datetime.date]:
] Python [CODE: datetime.date].
[ITALIC: In requests and responses will be represented as a [CODE: str] in ISO 8601 format, like: [CODE: 2008-09-15].
] [CODE: datetime.time]:
[ITALIC: A Python [CODE: datetime.time].
] In requests and responses will be represented as a [CODE: str] in ISO 8601 format, like: [CODE: 14:23:55.003].
[ITALIC: [CODE: datetime.timedelta]:
] A Python [CODE: datetime.timedelta].
[ITALIC: In requests and responses will be represented as a [CODE: float] of total seconds.
] Pydantic also allows representing it as a "ISO 8601 time diff encoding", see the docs for more info.
[ITALIC: [CODE: frozenset]:
] In requests and responses, treated the same as a [CODE: set]:
[ITALIC: In requests, a list will be read, eliminating duplicates and converting it to a [CODE: set].
] In responses, the [CODE: set] will be converted to a [CODE: list].
[ITALIC: The generated schema will specify that the [CODE: set] values are unique (using JSON Schema's [CODE: uniqueItems]).
] [CODE: bytes]:
[ITALIC: Standard Python [CODE: bytes].
] In requests and responses will be treated as [CODE: str].
[ITALIC: The generated schema will specify that it's a [CODE: str] with [CODE: binary] "format".
] [CODE: Decimal]:
[ITALIC: Standard Python [CODE: Decimal].
] In requests and responses, handled the same as a [CODE: float].
- You can check all the valid Pydantic data types here: Pydantic data types.

