## Recap
With [CODE: Query], [CODE: Path] (and others you haven't seen yet) you can declare metadata and string validations in the same ways as with Query Parameters and String Validations.
And you can also declare numeric validations:
[ITALIC: [CODE: gt]: [CODE: g]reater [CODE: t]han
] [CODE: ge]: [CODE: g]reater than or [CODE: e]qual
[ITALIC: [CODE: lt]: [CODE: l]ess [CODE: t]han
] [CODE: le]: [CODE: l]ess than or [CODE: e]qual
/// info
[CODE: Query], [CODE: Path], and other classes you will see later are subclasses of a common [CODE: Param] class.
All of them share the same parameters for additional validation and metadata you have seen.
///
/// note | Technical Details
When you import [CODE: Query], [CODE: Path] and others from [CODE: fastapi], they are actually functions.
That when called, return instances of classes of the same name.
So, you import [CODE: Query], which is a function. And when you call it, it returns an instance of a class also named [CODE: Query].
These functions are there (instead of just using the classes directly) so that your editor doesn't mark errors about their types.
That way you can use your normal editor and coding tools without having to add custom configurations to disregard those errors.
