## Custom Validation
There could be cases where you need to do some [BOLD:custom validation] that can't be done with the parameters shown above.
In those cases, you can use a [BOLD:custom validator function] that is applied after the normal validation (e.g. after validating that the value is a [CODE: str]).
You can achieve that using [Pydantic's [CODE: AfterValidator]](https://docs.pydantic.dev/latest/concepts/validators/#field-after-validator) inside of [CODE: Annotated].
/// tip
Pydantic also has [[CODE: BeforeValidator]](https://docs.pydantic.dev/latest/concepts/validators/#field-before-validator) and others. 🤓
///
For example, this custom validator checks that the item ID starts with [CODE: isbn-] for an ISBN book number or with [CODE: imdb-] for an IMDB movie URL ID:
```python
from pydantic import AfterValidator

def check[ITALIC:valid]id(id: str):
if not id.startswith(("isbn-", "imdb-")):
raise ValueError('Invalid ID format, it must start with "isbn-" or "imdb-"')
return id
id: Annotated[str | None, AfterValidator(check[ITALIC:valid]id)] = None,
):
```
/// info
This is available with Pydantic version 2 or above.
///
/// tip
If you need to do any type of validation that requires communicating with any [BOLD:external component], like a database or another API, you should instead use [BOLD:FastAPI Dependencies], you will learn about them later.
These custom validators are for things that can be checked with [BOLD:only] the [BOLD:same data] provided in the request.
///

