### [CODE: UploadFile]
[CODE: UploadFile] has the following attributes:
[ITALIC: [CODE: filename]: A [CODE: str] with the original file name that was uploaded (e.g. [CODE: myimage.jpg]).
] [CODE: content[ITALIC:type]: A [CODE: str] with the content type (MIME type / media type) (e.g. [CODE: image/jpeg]).
[ITALIC: [CODE: file]: A [[CODE: SpooledTemporaryFile]](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html#tempfile.SpooledTemporaryFile) (a file-like object). This is the actual Python file object that you can pass directly to other functions or libraries that expect a "file-like" object.
[CODE: UploadFile] has the following [CODE: async] methods. They all call the corresponding file methods underneath (using the internal [CODE: SpooledTemporaryFile]).
] [CODE: write(data)]: Writes [CODE: data] ([CODE: str] or [CODE: bytes]) to the file.
[ITALIC: [CODE: read(size)]: Reads [CODE: size] ([CODE: int]) bytes/characters of the file.
] [CODE: seek(offset)]: Goes to the byte position [CODE: offset] ([CODE: int]) in the file.
[ITALIC: E.g., [CODE: await myfile.seek(0)] would go to the start of the file.
] This is especially useful if you run [CODE: await myfile.read()] once and then need to read the contents again.
[ITALIC: [CODE: close()]: Closes the file.
As all these methods are [CODE: async] methods, you need to "await" them.
For example, inside of an [CODE: async] ]path operation function[ITALIC: you can get the contents with:
[CODE]BLOCK[ITALIC:0: contents = await myfile.read()...]
If you are inside of a normal [CODE: def] ]path operation function*, you can access the [CODE: UploadFile.file] directly, for example:
[CODE]BLOCK_1: contents = myfile.file.read()...]
/// note | [CODE: async] Technical Details
When you use the [CODE: async] methods, [BOLD:FastAPI] runs the file methods in a threadpool and awaits for them.
///
/// note | Starlette Technical Details
[BOLD:FastAPI]'s [CODE: UploadFile] inherits directly from [BOLD:Starlette]'s [CODE: UploadFile], but adds some necessary parts to make it compatible with [BOLD:Pydantic] and the other parts of FastAPI.
///

