# Form Models
You can use [BOLD:Pydantic models] to declare [BOLD:form fields] in FastAPI.
/// info
To use forms, first install [[CODE: python-multipart]](https://github.com/Kludex/python-multipart).
Make sure you create a virtual environment, activate it, and then install it, for example:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ pip install python-multipart...]
///
/// note
This is supported since FastAPI version [CODE: 0.113.0]. 🤓
///

[Context: Form Data > Define `Form` parameters]

## Define [CODE: Form] parameters
Create form parameters the same way you would for [CODE: Body] or [CODE: Query]:
```python
async def login(username: Annotated[str, Form()], password: Annotated[str, Form()]):
return {"username": username}
```
For example, in one of the ways the OAuth2 specification can be used (called "password flow") it is required to send a [CODE: username] and [CODE: password] as form fields.
The spec requires the fields to be exactly named [CODE: username] and [CODE: password], and to be sent as form fields, not JSON.
With [CODE: Form] you can declare the same configurations as with [CODE: Body] (and [CODE: Query], [CODE: Path], [CODE: Cookie]), including validation, examples, an alias (e.g. [CODE: user-name] instead of [CODE: username]), etc.
/// info
[CODE: Form] is a class that inherits directly from [CODE: Body].
///
/// tip
To declare form bodies, you need to use [CODE: Form] explicitly, because without it the parameters would be interpreted as query parameters or body (JSON) parameters.
///

