## About HTTP status codes
/// note
If you already know what HTTP status codes are, skip to the next section.
///
In HTTP, you send a numeric status code of 3 digits as part of the response.
These status codes have a name associated to recognize them, but the important part is the number.
In short:
[ITALIC: [CODE: 100 - 199] are for "Information". You rarely use them directly. Responses with these status codes cannot have a body.
] [BOLD:[CODE: 200 - 299]] are for "Successful" responses. These are the ones you would use the most.
[ITALIC: [CODE: 200] is the default status code, which means everything was "OK".
] Another example would be [CODE: 201], "Created". It is commonly used after creating a new record in the database.
[ITALIC: A special case is [CODE: 204], "No Content". This response is used when there is no content to return to the client, and so the response must not have a body.
] [BOLD:[CODE: 300 - 399]] are for "Redirection". Responses with these status codes may or may not have a body, except for [CODE: 304], "Not Modified", which must not have one.
[ITALIC: [BOLD:[CODE: 400 - 499]] are for "Client error" responses. These are the second type you would probably use the most.
] An example is [CODE: 404], for a "Not Found" response.
[ITALIC: For generic errors from the client, you can just use [CODE: 400].
] [CODE: 500 - 599] are for server errors. You almost never use them directly. When something goes wrong at some part in your application code, or server, it will automatically return one of these status codes.
/// tip
To know more about each status code and which code is for what, check the MDN documentation about HTTP status codes.
///

