# Stream JSON Lines
You could have a sequence of data that you would like to send in a "[BOLD:stream]", you could do it with [BOLD:JSON Lines].
/// info
Added in FastAPI 0.134.0.
///

[Context: Stream JSON Lines > JSON Lines]

## JSON Lines
In these cases, it's common to send "[BOLD:JSON Lines]", which is a format where you send one JSON object per line.
A response would have a content type of [CODE: application/jsonl] (instead of [CODE: application/json]) and the body would be something like:
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: {"name": "Plumbus", "description": "A multi-purpos...]
It's very similar to a JSON array (equivalent of a Python list), but instead of being wrapped in [CODE: []] and having [CODE: ,] between the items, it has [BOLD:one JSON object per line], they are separated by a new line character.
/// info
The important point is that your app will be able to produce each line in turn, while the client consumes the previous lines.
///
/// note | Technical Details
Because each JSON object will be separated by a new line, they can't contain literal new line characters in their content, but they can contain escaped new lines ([CODE: \n]), which is part of the JSON standard.
But normally you won't have to worry about it, it's done automatically, continue reading. 🤓
///

