# Dependencies with yield
FastAPI supports dependencies that do some extra steps after finishing.
To do this, use [CODE: yield] instead of [CODE: return], and write the extra steps (code) after.
/// tip
Make sure to use [CODE: yield] one single time per dependency.
///
/// note | Technical Details
Any function that is valid to use with:
[ITALIC: [[CODE: @contextlib.contextmanager]](https://docs.python.org/3/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.contextmanager) or
] [[CODE: @contextlib.asynccontextmanager]](https://docs.python.org/3/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.asynccontextmanager)
would be valid to use as a [BOLD:FastAPI] dependency.
In fact, FastAPI uses those two decorators internally.
///

[Context: Dependencies with yield > Execution of dependencies with `yield`]

## Execution of dependencies with [CODE: yield]
The sequence of execution is more or less like this diagram. Time flows from top to bottom. And each column is one of the parts interacting or executing code.
[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: sequenceDiagram participant client as Client parti...]
/// info
Only [BOLD:one response] will be sent to the client. It might be one of the error responses or it will be the response from the [ITALIC:path operation].
After one of those responses is sent, no other response can be sent.
///
/// tip
If you raise any exception in the code from the [ITALIC:path operation function], it will be passed to the dependencies with yield, including [CODE: HTTPException]. In most cases you will want to re-raise that same exception or a new one from the dependency with [CODE: yield] to make sure it's properly handled.
///

[Context: Dependencies with yield > Context Managers > Using context managers in dependencies with `yield`]

### Using context managers in dependencies with [CODE: yield]
/// warning
This is, more or less, an "advanced" idea.
If you are just starting with [BOLD:FastAPI] you might want to skip it for now.
///
In Python, you can create Context Managers by [creating a class with two methods: [CODE: [BOLD:enter]()] and [CODE: [BOLD:exit]()]](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#context-managers).
You can also use them inside of [BOLD:FastAPI] dependencies with [CODE: yield] by using
[CODE: with] or [CODE: async with] statements inside of the dependency function:
```python
class MySuperContextManager:
def [BOLD:init](self):
self.db = DBSession()

def [BOLD:enter](self):
return self.db

def [BOLD:exit](self, exc[ITALIC:type, exc]value, traceback):
self.db.close()
with MySuperContextManager() as db:
yield db
```
/// tip
Another way to create a context manager is with:
[ITALIC: [[CODE: @contextlib.contextmanager]](https://docs.python.org/3/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.contextmanager) or
] [[CODE: @contextlib.asynccontextmanager]](https://docs.python.org/3/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.asynccontextmanager)
using them to decorate a function with a single [CODE: yield].
That's what [BOLD:FastAPI] uses internally for dependencies with [CODE: yield].
But you don't have to use the decorators for FastAPI dependencies (and you shouldn't).
FastAPI will do it for you internally.
///

