## The [CODE: password] flow
Now let's go back a bit and understand what is all that.
The [CODE: password] "flow" is one of the ways ("flows") defined in OAuth2, to handle security and authentication.
OAuth2 was designed so that the backend or API could be independent of the server that authenticates the user.
But in this case, the same [BOLD:FastAPI] application will handle the API and the authentication.
So, let's review it from that simplified point of view:
[ITALIC: The user types the [CODE: username] and [CODE: password] in the frontend, and hits [CODE: Enter].
] The frontend (running in the user's browser) sends that [CODE: username] and [CODE: password] to a specific URL in our API (declared with [CODE: tokenUrl="token"]).
[ITALIC: The API checks that [CODE: username] and [CODE: password], and responds with a "token" (we haven't implemented any of this yet).
] A "token" is just a string with some content that we can use later to verify this user.
[ITALIC: Normally, a token is set to expire after some time.
] So, the user will have to log in again at some point later.
[ITALIC: And if the token is stolen, the risk is less. It is not like a permanent key that will work forever (in most of the cases).
] The frontend stores that token temporarily somewhere.
[ITALIC: The user clicks in the frontend to go to another section of the frontend web app.
] The frontend needs to fetch some more data from the API.
[ITALIC: But it needs authentication for that specific endpoint.
] So, to authenticate with our API, it sends a header [CODE: Authorization] with a value of [CODE: Bearer ] plus the token.
- If the token contains [CODE: foobar], the content of the [CODE: Authorization] header would be: [CODE: Bearer foobar].

